                            <comment id="17088115" author="paulk" created="Mon, 20 Apr 2020 21:57:36 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;In your particular case there is a workaround by changing the line with the error to:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;code panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre class=&quot;code-java&quot;&gt;
files?.sort(&lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;true&lt;/span&gt;) { File f -&amp;gt; f.name }
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;but that won&apos;t solve other cases.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17088665" author="davydotcom" created="Tue, 21 Apr 2020 13:10:45 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=paulk&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;paulk&quot;&gt;paulk&lt;/a&gt; . I figured out a workaround as well but thought this might merit some review.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17089707" author="emilles" created="Wed, 22 Apr 2020 14:07:52 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I will have a look to see if this is still happening in Groovy 2.5+.&#160; I think this has to do with the &lt;tt&gt;T[]&lt;/tt&gt; return type of the array sort extension methods.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You can also assign the result of the sort call to a temp. And I don&apos;t think you need the &quot;as File[]&quot;. You can use &lt;tt&gt;&amp;lt;=&amp;gt;&lt;/tt&gt; operator in place of &lt;tt&gt;compareTo&lt;/tt&gt;. And if you are comparing one property in natural order, you can use a variant of sort that just returns that property from the closure.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;code panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre class=&quot;code-groovy&quot;&gt;
File file = &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;new&lt;/span&gt; File(&lt;span class=&quot;code-quote&quot;&gt;&apos;.&apos;&lt;/span&gt;)
listSortedFiles(file)

@groovy.transform.CompileStatic
void listSortedFiles(File directory) {
  File[] files = directory.listFiles()
  &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;def&lt;/span&gt; sorted = files?.sort { it.name }
  &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;for&lt;/span&gt; (file &lt;span class=&quot;code-keyword&quot;&gt;in&lt;/span&gt; sorted) {
    println file.name
  }
}
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17089714" author="emilles" created="Wed, 22 Apr 2020 14:17:44 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Note: Declaring &lt;tt&gt;files&lt;/tt&gt; with &quot;def&quot; instead of &lt;tt&gt;File[]&lt;/tt&gt; is another available workaround.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="17107822" author="paulk" created="Fri, 15 May 2020 01:24:02 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;ported to 2_5_X&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
